      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "Route app-owned web egress through managed proxy path",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nThis PR moves ordinary app-owned web/media/download egress onto a neutral app fetch transport so the managed runtime proxy is the central place for outbound destination policy.\n\nKey behavior changes:\n\n- `web_fetch`, app-owned media URL reads, marketplace downloads, skill artifact downloads, and remote tool-definition downloads no longer apply `web_fetch`-local private-network SSRF blocking by default.\n- When `proxy.enabled=true`, supported runtime fetch traffic is routed through the operator-managed proxy where private-network and destination policy should be enforced.\n- `tools.web.fetch.useTrustedEnvProxy` and `tools.web.fetch.ssrfPolicy` are retired. `openclaw doctor --fix` removes those keys and emits a migration warning that points operators to `proxy.enabled` plus external proxy policy.\n- Explicit input-file hostname allowlists still apply across redirects.\n- Credentialed provider endpoint fetches remain guarded.\n- `web_fetch` provider fallback remains a third-party boundary: OpenClaw does not delegate localhost/private/link-local/metadata/special-use/private-DNS URLs or redirect target URLs to external web-fetch providers.\n- `tools.web.fetch.readability=false` remains provider-only and delegates the original requested URL before any local fetch.\n\n## Verification\n\n- Focused Vitest coverage passed for web_fetch provider fallback, trusted provider endpoint redirects, app fetch transport redirects, media fetch, input-file URL allowlists, and policy doctor cleanup.\n- TypeScript checks passed for core, test source, and extensions.\n- Markdown docs listing passed.\n- `git diff --check` passed.\n- Crabbox E2E passed for representative affected flows: direct loopback/private web_fetch and media fetch, managed proxy observation and proxy denial, cross-origin redirect credential/body stripping, URL-backed media ingestion, media-understanding URL cache fetch, marketplace archive download, skill artifact download, and remote tool-definition download/install/execute.\n\nProvider-fallback private/redirect/readability behavior is covered by focused tests rather than live third-party provider calls, because the important invariant is whether OpenClaw delegates a URL to the provider at all.\n",
        "branch": "refactor/app-web-egress-proxy-pr1",
